subSubSection.paragraph:
Palp
(
Figs 3
, 
5
). Femur long, 2 times longer than tibia. Tibia as long as cymbium, with setae of different length, especially with denser setae on the retrolateral side of the distal end. Cymbium subtriangular, covered by dense setae dorsally. Cymbial apex extended outward forming “vexillum” (
Ve
). Paracymbium developed, plump, slightly extending towards prolateral side, with a subtriangular outgrowth distally. Subtegulum semicircular. Tegulum with a prolateral apophysis (
Ta
). Conductor cylindrical, strongly sclerotized, and extending outward. Embolus heavily sclerotized, originating the position between 7 and 8 o’clock and extending clockwise for 90º.

